        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I don't really see the point of maintaining these files (nix.flake and flake.lock) as part of our repo. Apparently these files are not nearly close to be \"self contained\" in any sense of the word, but depend on hash references to custom specific versions of the Nixpkgs repo.\r\n\r\nThe nix package is kinda similar to flatpak/docker. You can run the latest nvim with it. The added benefit is that it gives you also a dev environment with `nix develop ./contrib` (or `nix develop 'github:neovim/neovim?dir=contrib` if you haven't cloned it yet). Ofc the build breaks may break when we update dependencies but that's part of the deal: it's best effort, no new pipelines etc.\r\n\r\nI understand if the team wants to remove it since it's not a core aspect of neovim but I guess nix builds makes for the most reproducible builds, making debugging easier. I use the `nix develop` to develop on neovim (less recently) but there are other users. \r\nI feel like it is low maintainance (@dundargoc let me know if you disagree), just let me deal with those PRs. If I get hit by a bus, feel free to nuke the files.",
